The Roc Road is the primary overland trade corridor connecting Midgaard (east) to Kiess (west).
Kiess was built on the ruins of Evermeet, which formerly anchored the western end.
The road has four historical layers: pre-city migration track, formalized stone route with mile markers, war-era military supply corridor, post-war mercantile spine.

Eastern half: Midgaard-controlled. Gray-purple ash-mortar paving from the Lantern Reforms. Patrol relays, checkpoint oath recitations, boundary sigils maintained per the Oath of Stone. Wardens recite the Three Civic Oaths at each shift change.
Western half: Kiess-controlled. Managed by convoy marshals using convoy compacts (shared liability pools). Marshals can delay departures, reroute through the Greenveil Spur, or pay wayfolk for emergency guide services.
Central Crossroads: disputed zone where charter boundaries overlap. Independent actors operate here. Violence increases under unilateral control attempts. Shared governance reduces bloodshed but breeds corruption.

The Violet Eclipse Cathedral stands along the route. It predates both cities. Its procurement ledgers and binding archives are significant and controversial.
Kiess founding clause: no sealed warrant from a predecessor authority binds a Kiess citizen. This directly repudiates abuses committed under the road's eastern administration.
Core tension: Midgaard asks "Who has lawful right to command?" Kiess asks "What keeps goods and people alive tomorrow?" The road's identity rests on this unresolved conflict.

